1.2: Always returns false.
Always returns NULL.
Always returns true.

Creates a function that returns true if each of its components evaluates to true. The components are evaluated in order, and the evaluation will be short-circuited as soon as a function returns false. For example, (goog.functions.and(f, g))(x) is equivalent to f(x) && g(x).
A list of functions.
A function that ANDs its component functions.

Gives a wrapper function that caches the return value of a parameterless function when first called.

When called for the first time, the given function is called and its return value is cached (thus this is only appropriate for idempotent functions). Subsequent calls will return the cached return value. This allows the evaluation of expensive functions to be delayed until first used.

To cache the return values of functions with parameters, see goog.memoize.
A function to lazily evaluate.
A wrapped version the function.
Creates the composition of the functions passed in. For example, (goog.functions.compose(f, g))(a) is equivalent to f(g(a)).
The final function.
A list of functions.
The composition of all inputs.
Creates a function that always returns the same value.
The value to return.
The new function.

Generic factory function to construct an object given the constructor and the arguments. Intended to be bound to create object factories.

Example:

var factory = goog.partial(goog.functions.create, Class);
The constructor for the Object.
The arguments to be passed to the constructor.
A new instance of the class given in constructor.

Wraps a function to allow it to be called, at most, once for each sequence of calls fired repeatedly so long as they are fired less than a specified interval apart (in milliseconds). Whether it receives one signal or multiple, it will always wait until a full interval has elapsed since the last signal before performing the action, passing the arguments from the last call of the debouncing decorator into the decorated function.

This is particularly useful for bulking up repeated user actions (e.g. only refreshing a view once a user finishes typing rather than updating with every keystroke). For more stateful debouncing with support for pausing, resuming, and canceling debounced actions, use goog.async.Debouncer.
Function to call.
Interval over which to debounce. The function will only be called after the full interval has elapsed since the last call.
Object in whose scope to call the function.
Wrapped function.

Creates a function that returns whether its argument equals the given value.

Example: var key = goog.object.findKey(obj, goog.functions.equalTo('needle'));
The value to compare to.
Whether to use a loose (==) comparison rather than a strict (===) one. Defaults to false.
The new function.
Creates a function that always throws an error with the given message.
The error message.
The error-throwing function.
Creates a function that throws the given object.
An object to be thrown.
The error-throwing function.
A simple function that returns the first argument of whatever is passed into it.
The single value that will be returned.
Optional trailing arguments. These are ignored.
The first argument passed in, or undefined if nothing was passed.
Given a function, create a function that keeps opt_numArgs arguments and silently discards all additional arguments.
The original function.
The number of arguments to keep. Defaults to 0.
A version of f that only keeps the first opt_numArgs arguments.
Creates a function that returns the Boolean opposite of a provided function. For example, (goog.functions.not(f))(x) is equivalent to !f(x).
The original function.
A function that delegates to f and returns opposite.
Creates a function that returns its nth argument.
The position of the return argument.
A new function.

Wraps a function to allow it to be called, at most, once. All additional calls are no-ops.

This is particularly useful for initialization functions that should be called, at most, once.
Function to call.
Wrapped function.

Creates a function that returns true if any of its components evaluates to true. The components are evaluated in order, and the evaluation will be short-circuited as soon as a function returns true. For example, (goog.functions.or(f, g))(x) is equivalent to f(x) || g(x).
A list of functions.
A function that ORs its component functions.

Like goog.partial(), except that arguments are added after arguments to the returned function.

Usage: function f(arg1, arg2, arg3, arg4) { ... } var g = goog.functions.partialRight(f, arg3, arg4); g(arg1, arg2);
A function to partially apply.
Additional arguments that are partially applied to fn at the end.
A partially-applied form of the function goog.partial() was invoked as a method of.
Creates a function that calls the functions passed in in sequence, and returns the value of the last function. For example, (goog.functions.sequence(f, g))(x) is equivalent to f(x),g(x).
A list of functions.
A function that calls all inputs in sequence.

Wraps a function to allow it to be called, at most, once per interval (specified in milliseconds). If it is called multiple times while it is waiting, it will only perform the action once at the end of the interval, passing the arguments from the last call of the throttling decorator into the decorated function.

This is particularly useful for limiting repeated user requests (e.g. preventing a user from spamming a server with frequent view refreshes). For more stateful throttling with support for pausing, resuming, and canceling throttled actions, use goog.async.Throttle.
Function to call.
Interval over which to throttle. The function can only be called once per interval.
Object in whose scope to call the function.
Wrapped function.
Given a function, create a new function that swallows its return value and replaces it with a new one.
A function.
A new return value.
A new function.
Whether the return value cache should be used. This should only be used to disable caches when testing.
